# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: edgedb
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:edgedb/blob-readme-md] Gel is a new kind of database that takes the best parts of relational databases, graph databases, and ORMs.
[src:edgedb/blob-readme-md] We call it a **graph-relational database**.
[src:edgedb/blob-readme-md] Schema is the foundation of your application.
[src:edgedb/blob-readme-md] It should be something you can read, write, and understand.
[src:edgedb/blob-readme-md] Forget foreign keys; tabular data modeling is a relic of an older age, and it isn't compatible with modern languages.
[src:edgedb/blob-readme-md] Instead, Gel thinks about schema the same way you do: as **object types** containing **properties** connected by **links**.
[src:edgedb/blob-readme-md] This example is intentionally simple, but Gel supports everything you'd expect from your database: a strict type system, indexes, constraints, computed properties, stored procedures...the list goes on.
[src:edgedb/blob-readme-md] Plus it gives you some shiny new features too: link properties, schema mixins, and best-in-class JSON support.
[src:edgedb/blob-readme-md] Gel's super-powered query language EdgeQL is designed as a ground-up redesign of SQL.
[src:edgedb/blob-readme-md] EdgeQL queries produce rich, structured objects, not flat lists of rows.
[src:edgedb/blob-readme-md] Deeply fetching related objects is painless...bye, bye, JOINs.
[src:edgedb/blob-readme-md] EdgeQL queries are also *composable*; you can use one EdgeQL query as an expression inside another.
[src:edgedb/blob-readme-md] This property makes things like *subqueries* and *nested mutations* a breeze.
[src:edgedb/blob-readme-md] There's a lot more to EdgeQL: a comprehensive standard library, computed properties, polymorphic queries, `with` blocks, transactions, and much more.
[src:edgedb/blob-readme-md] Read the EdgeQL docs for the full picture.
[src:edgedb/blob-readme-md] While Gel solves the same problems as ORM libraries, it's so much more.
[src:edgedb/blob-readme-md] It's a full-fledged database with a powerful and elegant query language, a migrations system, a suite of client libraries in different languages, a command line tool, and a managed cloud service.
[src:edgedb/blob-readme-md] The goal is to rethink every aspect of how developers model, migrate, manage, and query their database.
[src:edgedb/blob-readme-md] Here's a taste-test of Gel's next-level developer experience: you can install our CLI, spin up an instance, and open an interactive EdgeQL shell with just three commands.
[src:edgedb/blob-readme-md] Windows users: use this Powershell command to install the CLI.
[src:edgedb/blob-readme-md] To get started, follow this guide to build Gel from source on your local machine.
[src:edgedb/blob-readme-md] The code in this repository is developed and distributed under the Apache 2.0 license.
[src:edgedb/database-schema] The **database schema** is the structure of a database described in a formal language supported typically by a relational database management system (RDBMS).
[src:edgedb/database-schema] The term "schema" refers to the organization of data as a blueprint of how the database is constructed (divided into database tables in the case of relational databases).
[src:edgedb/database-schema] The formal definition of a database schema is a set of formulas (sentences) called integrity constraints imposed on a database.
[src:edgedb/database-schema] These integrity constraints ensure compatibility between parts of the schema.
[src:edgedb/database-schema] All constraints are expressible in the same language.
[src:edgedb/database-schema] A database can be considered a structure in realization of the database language.
[src:edgedb/database-schema] The states of a created conceptual schema are transformed into an explicit mapping, the database schema.
[src:edgedb/database-schema] This describes how real-world entities are modeled in the database.
[src:edgedb/database-schema] "A database schema specifies, based on the database administrator's knowledge of possible applications, the facts that can enter the database, or those of interest to the possible end-users." The notion of a database schema plays the same role as the notion of theory in predicate calculus.
[src:edgedb/database-schema] A model of this "theory" closely corresponds to a database, which can be seen at any instant of time as a mathematical object.
[src:edgedb/database-schema] Thus a schema can contain formulas representing integrity constraints specifically for an application and the constraints specifically for a type of database, all expressed in the same database language.
[src:edgedb/database-schema] In a relational database, the schema defines the tables, fields, relationships, views, indexes, packages, procedures, functions, queues, triggers, types, sequences, materialized views, synonyms, database links, directories, XML schemas, and other elements.
[src:edgedb/database-schema] A database generally stores its schema in a data dictionary.
[src:edgedb/database-schema] Although a schema is defined in text database language, the term is often used to refer to a graphical depiction of the database structure.
[src:edgedb/database-schema] In other words, schema is the structure of the database that defines the objects in the database.
[src:edgedb/database-schema] In an Oracle Database system, the term "schema" has a slightly different connotation.
[src:edgedb/database-schema] The requirements listed below influence the detailed structure of schemas that are produced.
[src:edgedb/database-schema] Certain applications will not require that all of these conditions are met, but these four requirements are the most ideal.
[src:edgedb/database-schema] Each of the overlapping elements specified in the input mapping is also in a database schema relation.
[src:edgedb/database-schema] Source-specific elements that are associated with a source’s overlapping elements are passed through to the database schema.
[src:edgedb/database-schema] Independent entities and relationships in the source data should not be grouped together in the same relation in the database schema.
[src:edgedb/database-schema] In particular, source specific schema elements should not be grouped with overlapping schema elements, if the grouping co-locates independent entities or relationships.
[src:edgedb/database-schema] If any elements of the database schema are dropped then the database schema is not ideal.
[src:edgedb/database-schema] Suppose we want a mediated schema to integrate two travel databases, Go-travel and Ok-flight.
[src:edgedb/database-schema] In the context of Oracle Databases, a **schema object** is a logical data storage structure.
[src:edgedb/database-schema] An Oracle database associates a separate schema with each database **user**.
[src:edgedb/database-schema] A schema comprises a collection of schema objects.
[src:edgedb/database-schema] Schema objects do not have a one-to-one correspondence to physical files on disk that store their information.
[src:edgedb/database-schema] However, Oracle databases store schema objects logically within a tablespace of the database.
[src:edgedb/database-schema] The data of each object is physically contained in one or more of the tablespace's datafiles.
[src:edgedb/database-schema] For some objects (such as tables, indexes, and clusters) a database administrator can specify how much disk space the Oracle RDBMS allocates for the object within the tablespace's datafiles.
[src:edgedb/database-schema] There is no necessary relationship between schemas and tablespaces: a tablespace can contain objects from different schemas, and the objects for a single schema can reside in different tablespaces.
[src:edgedb/database-schema] Oracle database specificity does, however, enforce platform recognition of nonhomogenized sequence differentials, which is considered a crucial limiting factor in virtualized applications.
[src:edgedb/database-schema] In Microsoft SQL Server, the default schema of every database is the dbo schema.
[src:edgedb/docs-geldata-com] Gel is a next-generation graph-relational database designed as a spiritual successor to the relational database.
[src:edgedb/docs-geldata-com] It inherits the strengths of SQL databases: type safety, performance, reliability, and transactionality.
[src:edgedb/docs-geldata-com] But instead of modeling data in a relational (tabular) way, Gel represents data with *object types* containing *properties* and *links* to other objects.
[src:edgedb/docs-geldata-com] It leverages this object-oriented model to provide a superpowered query language that solves some of SQL's biggest usability problems.
[src:edgedb/docs-geldata-com] Gel is a complex system, but we've structured the documentation so you can learn it in "phases".
[src:edgedb/docs-geldata-com] You only need to learn as much as you need to start building your application.
[src:edgedb/docs-geldata-com] To actually build apps with Gel, you'll need to know more than SDL and EdgeQL.
[src:edgedb/docs-geldata-com] Gel is not a graph database: the data is stored and queried using relational database techniques.
[src:edgedb/docs-geldata-com] Unlike most graph databases, Gel maintains a strict schema.
[src:edgedb/docs-geldata-com] Gel is not a document database, but inserting and querying hierarchical document-like data is trivial.
[src:edgedb/docs-geldata-com] Gel is not a traditional object database, despite the classification, it is not an implementation of OOP persistence.
[src:edgedb/object-relational-mapping] In object-oriented programming, data-management tasks act on objects that combine scalar values into objects.
[src:edgedb/object-relational-mapping] For example, consider an address book entry that represents a single person along with zero or more phone numbers and zero or more addresses.
[src:edgedb/object-relational-mapping] This could be modeled in an object-oriented implementation by a "Person object" with an attribute/field to hold each data item that the entry comprises: the person's name, a list of phone numbers, and a list of addresses.
[src:edgedb/object-relational-mapping] The list of phone numbers would itself contain "PhoneNumber objects" and so on.
[src:edgedb/object-relational-mapping] Each such address-book entry is treated as a single object by the programming language (it can be referenced by a single variable containing a pointer to the object, for instance).
[src:edgedb/object-relational-mapping] Various methods can be associated with the object, such as methods to return the preferred phone number, the home address, and so on.
[src:edgedb/object-relational-mapping] By contrast, relational databases, such as SQL, group scalars into tuples, which are then enumerated in tables.
[src:edgedb/object-relational-mapping] Tuples and objects have some general similarity, in that they are both ways to collect values into named fields such that the whole collection can be manipulated as a single compound entity.
[src:edgedb/object-relational-mapping] They have many differences, though, in particular: lifecycle management (row insertion and deletion, versus garbage collection or reference counting), references to other entities (object references, versus foreign key references), and inheritance (non-existent in relational databases).
[src:edgedb/object-relational-mapping] As well, objects are managed on-heap and are under full control of a single process, while database tuples are shared and must incorporate locking, merging, and retry.
[src:edgedb/object-relational-mapping] Object–relational mapping provides automated support for mapping tuples to objects and back, while accounting for all of these differences.
[src:edgedb/object-relational-mapping] The heart of the problem involves translating the logical representation of the objects into an atomized form that is capable of being stored in the database while preserving the properties of the objects and their relationships so that they can be reloaded as objects when needed.
[src:edgedb/object-relational-mapping] If this storage and retrieval functionality is implemented, the objects are said to be persistent.
[src:edgedb/object-relational-mapping] Implementation-specific details of storage drivers are generally wrapped in an API in the programming language in use, exposing methods to interact with the storage medium in a way which is simpler and more in line with the paradigms of surrounding code.
[src:edgedb/object-relational-mapping] The following is a simple example, written in C# code, to execute a query written in SQL using a database engine.
[src:edgedb/object-relational-mapping] In contrast, the following makes use of an ORM-job API which makes it possible to write code that naturally makes use of the features of the language.
[src:edgedb/object-relational-mapping] The case above makes use of an object representing the storage repository and methods of that object.
[src:edgedb/object-relational-mapping] Other frameworks might provide code as static methods, as in the example below, and yet other methods may not implement an object-oriented system at all.
[src:edgedb/object-relational-mapping] Often the choice of paradigm is made for the best fit of the ORM into the surrounding language's design principles.
[src:edgedb/object-relational-mapping] Compared to traditional techniques of exchange between an object-oriented language and a relational database, ORM often reduces the amount of code that needs to be written.
[src:edgedb/object-relational-mapping] Disadvantages of ORM tools generally stem from the high level of abstraction obscuring what is actually happening in the implementation code.
[src:edgedb/object-relational-mapping] Another approach is to use an object-oriented database management system (OODBMS) or document-oriented databases such as native XML databases that provide more flexibility in data modeling.
[src:edgedb/object-relational-mapping] OODBMSs are databases designed specifically for working with object-oriented values.
[src:edgedb/object-relational-mapping] Using an OODBMS eliminates the need for converting data to and from its SQL form, as the data is stored in its original object representation and relationships are directly represented, rather than requiring join tables/operations.
[src:edgedb/object-relational-mapping] The equivalent of ORMs for document-oriented databases are called object-document mappers (ODMs).
[src:edgedb/object-relational-mapping] Document-oriented databases also prevent the user from having to "shred" objects into table rows.
[src:edgedb/object-relational-mapping] Many of these systems also support the XQuery query language to retrieve datasets.
[src:edgedb/object-relational-mapping] Object-oriented databases tend to be used in complex, niche applications.
[src:edgedb/object-relational-mapping] One of the arguments against using an OODBMS is that it may not be able to execute ad-hoc, application-independent queries.
[src:edgedb/object-relational-mapping] For this reason, many programmers find themselves more at home with an object-SQL mapping system, even though most object-oriented databases are able to process SQL queries to a limited extent.
[src:edgedb/object-relational-mapping] Other OODBMS provide replication to SQL databases, as a means of addressing the need for ad-hoc queries, while preserving well-known query patterns.
[src:edgedb/object-relational-mapping] A variety of difficulties arise when considering how to match an object system to a relational database.
[src:edgedb/object-relational-mapping] These difficulties are referred to as the object–relational impedance mismatch.
[src:edgedb/object-relational-mapping] An alternative to implementing ORM is use of the native procedural languages provided with every major database.
[src:edgedb/object-relational-mapping] These can be called from the client using SQL statements.
[src:edgedb/object-relational-mapping] The Data Access Object (DAO) design pattern is used to abstract these statements and offer a lightweight object-oriented interface to the rest of the application.
[src:edgedb/object-relational-mapping] ORMs are limited to their predefined functionality, which may not cover all edge cases or database features.
[src:edgedb/object-relational-mapping] They usually mitigate this limitation by providing users with an interface to write raw queries, such as Django ORM.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] The PostgreSQL Global Development Group focuses only on developing a database engine and closely related components.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] This core is, technically, what comprises PostgreSQL itself, but there is an extensive developer community and ecosystem that provides other important feature sets that might, traditionally, be provided by a proprietary software vendor.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] These include special-purpose database engine features, like those needed to support a geospatial or temporal database or features which emulate other database products.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Also available from third parties are a wide variety of user and machine interface features, such as graphical user interfaces or load balancing and high availability toolsets.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] The large third-party PostgreSQL support network of people, companies, products, and projects, even though not part of The PostgreSQL Development Group, are essential to the PostgreSQL database engine's adoption and use and make up the PostgreSQL ecosystem writ large.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] PostgreSQL was originally named POSTGRES, referring to its origins as a successor to the Ingres database developed at the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] In 1996, the project was renamed PostgreSQL to reflect its support for SQL.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] After a review in 2007, the development team decided to keep the name PostgreSQL and the alias Postgres.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] PostgreSQL evolved from the Ingres project at the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] In 1982, the leader of the Ingres team, Michael Stonebraker, left Berkeley to make a proprietary version of Ingres.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] He returned to Berkeley in 1985, and began a post-Ingres project to address the problems with contemporary database systems that had become increasingly clear during the early 1980s.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] He won the Turing Award in 2014 for these and other projects, and techniques pioneered in them.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] The new project, POSTGRES, aimed to add the fewest features needed to completely support data types.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] These features included the ability to define types and to fully describe relationships – something used widely, but maintained entirely by the user.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] In POSTGRES, the database understood relationships, and could retrieve information in related tables in a natural way using *rules*.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] POSTGRES used many of the ideas of Ingres, but not its code.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Starting in 1986, published papers described the basis of the system, and a prototype version was shown at the 1988 ACM SIGMOD Conference.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] The team released version 1 to a small number of users in June 1989, followed by version 2 with a re-written rules system in June 1990.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Version 3, released in 1991, again re-wrote the rules system, and added support for multiple storage managers and an improved query engine.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] By 1993, the number of users began to overwhelm the project with requests for support and features.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] After releasing version 4.2 on June 30, 1994 – primarily a cleanup – the project ended.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Berkeley released POSTGRES under an MIT License variant, which enabled other developers to use the code for any use.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] At the time, POSTGRES used an Ingres-influenced POSTQUEL query language interpreter, which could be interactively used with a console application named monitor.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] In 1994, Berkeley graduate students Andrew Yu and Jolly Chen replaced the POSTQUEL query language interpreter with one for the SQL query language, creating Postgres95.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] The monitor console was also replaced by psql.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Yu and Chen announced the first version (0.01) to beta testers on May 5, 1995.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Version 1.0 of Postgres95 was announced on September 5, 1995, with a more liberal license that enabled the software to be freely modifiable.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] On July 8, 1996, Marc Fournier at Hub.org Networking Services provided the first non-university development server for the open-source development effort.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] With the participation of Bruce Momjian and Vadim B.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Mikheev, work began to stabilize the code inherited from Berkeley.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] In 1996, the project was renamed to PostgreSQL to reflect its support for SQL.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] The online presence at the website PostgreSQL.org began on October 22, 1996.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] The first PostgreSQL release formed version 6.0 on January 29, 1997.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Since then developers and volunteers around the world have maintained the software as The PostgreSQL Global Development Group.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] The project continues to make releases available under its free and open-source software PostgreSQL License.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Code comes from contributions from proprietary vendors, support companies, and open-source programmers.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] As of 2025, PostgreSQL is on major release version 18 which is notable in implementing asynchronous I/O (AIO), enabling database users to perform concurrent I/O tasks like readahead and sequential scan.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] PostgreSQL manages concurrency through multiversion concurrency control (MVCC), which gives each transaction a "snapshot" of the database, allowing changes to be made without affecting other transactions.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] This largely eliminates the need for read locks, and ensures the database maintains ACID principles.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] PostgreSQL offers four levels of transaction isolation: Read Uncommitted, Read Committed, Repeatable Read and Serializable.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Because PostgreSQL is immune to dirty reads, requesting a Read Uncommitted transaction isolation level provides read committed instead.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] PostgreSQL supports full serializability via the serializable snapshot isolation (SSI) method.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] The PostgreSQL MVCC implementation is prone to performance issues that require tuning when under a heavy write load which updates existing rows.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] PostgreSQL includes built-in binary replication based on shipping the changes (write-ahead logs (WAL)) to replica nodes asynchronously, with the ability to run read-only queries against these replicated nodes.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] This allows splitting read traffic among multiple nodes efficiently.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Earlier replication software that allowed similar read scaling normally relied on adding replication triggers to the master, increasing load.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] PostgreSQL includes built-in synchronous replication that ensures that, for each write transaction, the master waits until at least one replica node has written the data to its transaction log.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Unlike other database systems, the durability of a transaction (whether it is asynchronous or synchronous) can be specified per-database, per-user, per-session or even per-transaction.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] This can be useful for workloads that do not require such guarantees, and may not be wanted for all data as it slows down performance due to the requirement of the confirmation of the transaction reaching the synchronous standby.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Standby servers can be synchronous or asynchronous.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Synchronous standby servers can be specified in the configuration which determines which servers are candidates for synchronous replication.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] The first in the list that is actively streaming will be used as the current synchronous server.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] When this fails, the system fails over to the next in line.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] PostgreSQL's replication can trigger conflicts between the primary and standby servers, particularly whenever tuples are prematurely deleted from the standby server despite ongoing queries accessing them.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] To address this, PostgreSQL includes a feedback flag where the standby server proactively informs the primary server of any ongoing queries to mitigate this type of conflict.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Synchronous multi-master replication is not included in the PostgreSQL core.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Postgres-XC which is based on PostgreSQL provides scalable synchronous multi-master replication.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] It is licensed under the same license as PostgreSQL.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] A related project is called Postgres-XL.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Bidirectional replication (BDR) is an asynchronous multi-master replication system for PostgreSQL.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Tools such as repmgr make managing replication clusters easier.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Several asynchronous trigger-based replication packages are available.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] PostgreSQL includes built-in support for regular B-tree and hash table indexes, and four index access methods: generalized search trees (GiST), generalized inverted indexes (GIN), Space-Partitioned GiST (SP-GiST) and Block Range Indexes (BRIN).
[src:edgedb/postgresql] In addition, user-defined index methods can be created, although this is quite an involved process.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] PostgreSQL schemas are namespaces, allowing objects of the same kind and name to co-exist in a single database.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] They are not to be confused with a database schema—the abstract, structural, organizational specification which defines how every table's data relates to data within other tables.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] All PostgreSQL database objects, except for a few global objects such as roles and tablespaces, exist within a schema.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] They cannot be nested, schemas cannot contain schemas.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] The permission system controls access to schemas and their content.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] By default, newly created databases have only a single schema called *public* but other schemas can be added and the public schema isn't mandatory.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] A `search_path` setting determines the order in which PostgreSQL checks schemas for unqualified objects (those without a prefixed schema).
[src:edgedb/postgresql] By default, it is set to `$user, public` (`$user` refers to the currently connected database user).
[src:edgedb/postgresql] This default can be set on a database or role level, but as it is a session parameter, it can be freely changed (even multiple times) during a client session, affecting that session only.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Non-existent schemas, or other schemas not accessible to the logged-in user, that are listed in search_path are silently skipped during object lookup.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] New objects are created in whichever valid schema (one that can be accessed) appears first in the search_path.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] In addition, users can create their own data types which can usually be made fully indexable via PostgreSQL's indexing infrastructures – GiST, GIN, SP-GiST.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Examples of these include the geographic information system (GIS) data types from the PostGIS project for PostgreSQL.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] There is also a data type called a *domain*, which is the same as any other data type but with optional constraints defined by the creator of that domain.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] This means any data entered into a column using the domain will have to conform to whichever constraints were defined as part of the domain.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] A data type that represents a range of data can be used which are called range types.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] These can be discrete ranges (e.g. all integer values 1 to 10) or continuous ranges (e.g., any time between 10:00 am and 11:00 am).
[src:edgedb/postgresql] The built-in range types available include ranges of integers, big integers, decimal numbers, time stamps (with and without time zone) and dates.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Custom range types can be created to make new types of ranges available, such as IP address ranges using the inet type as a base, or float ranges using the float data type as a base.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Range types support inclusive and exclusive range boundaries using the [] and () characters respectively.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] (e.g., `[4,9)` represents all integers starting from and including 4 up to but not including 9.) Range types are also compatible with existing operators used to check for overlap, containment, right of etc.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Tables can be set to inherit their characteristics from a *parent* table.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Data in child tables will appear to exist in the parent tables, unless data is selected from the parent table using the ONLY keyword, i.e.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Adding a column in the parent table will cause that column to appear in the child table.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Inheritance can be used to implement table partitioning, using either triggers or rules to direct inserts to the parent table into the proper child tables.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] In particular, table constraints are not currently inheritable.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] All check constraints and not-null constraints on a parent table are automatically inherited by its children.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Other types of constraints (unique, primary key, and foreign key constraints) are not inherited.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Inheritance provides a way to map the features of generalization hierarchies depicted in entity–relationship diagrams (ERDs) directly into the PostgreSQL database.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] PostgreSQL can link to other systems to retrieve data via foreign data wrappers (FDWs).
[src:edgedb/postgresql] These can take the form of any data source, such as a file system, another relational database management system (RDBMS), or a web service.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] This means that regular database queries can use these data sources like regular tables, and even join multiple data-sources together.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] PostgreSQL supports a binary communication protocol that allows applications to connect to the database server.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] The protocol is versioned (currently 3.0, as of PostgreSQL 7.4) and has a detailed specification.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] The official client implementation of this communication protocol is a C API, libpq.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] In addition, the officially supported ECPG tool allows SQL commands to be embedded in C code.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Both are part of the standard PostgreSQL distribution.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Third-party libraries for connecting to PostgreSQL are available for many programming languages, including C++, Java, Julia, Python, Node.js, Go, and Rust.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Procedural languages allow developers to extend the database with custom subroutines (functions), often called *stored procedures*.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] These functions can be used to build database triggers (functions invoked on modification of certain data) and custom data types and aggregate functions.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Procedural languages can also be invoked without defining a function, using a DO command at SQL level.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Languages are divided into two groups: Procedures written in *safe* languages are sandboxed and can be safely created and used by any user.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Procedures written in *unsafe* languages can only be created by superusers, because they allow bypassing a database's security restrictions, but can also access sources external to the database.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Some languages like Perl provide both safe and unsafe versions.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] In addition, PostgreSQL allows procedural languages to be loaded into the database through extensions.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Three language extensions are included with PostgreSQL to support Perl, Tcl, and Python.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] For Python, the current Python 3 is used, and the discontinued Python 2 is no longer supported as of PostgreSQL 15.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Both were supported previously, defaulting to Python 2, while old and new versions couldn't be used in the same session.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] External projects provide support for many other languages, including PL/Java, JavaScript (PL/V8), PL/Julia, PL/R, PL/Ruby, and others.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Triggers are events triggered by the action of SQL data manipulation language (DML) statements.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] For example, an INSERT statement might activate a trigger that checks if the values of the statement are valid.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Most triggers are only activated by either INSERT or UPDATE statements.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Triggers are fully supported and can be attached to tables.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Triggers can be per-column and conditional, in that UPDATE triggers can target specific columns of a table, and triggers can be told to execute under a set of conditions as specified in the trigger's WHERE clause.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Triggers can be attached to views by using the INSTEAD OF condition.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Multiple triggers are fired in alphabetical order.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] In addition to calling functions written in the native PL/pgSQL, triggers can also invoke functions written in other languages like PL/Python or PL/Perl.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] PostgreSQL provides an asynchronous messaging system that is accessed through the NOTIFY, LISTEN and UNLISTEN commands.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] A session can issue a NOTIFY command, along with the user-specified channel and an optional payload, to mark a particular event occurring.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Other sessions are able to detect these events by issuing a LISTEN command, which can listen to a particular channel.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] This functionality can be used for a wide variety of purposes, such as letting other sessions know when a table has updated or for separate applications to detect when a particular action has been performed.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Such a system prevents the need for continuous polling by applications to see if anything has yet changed, and reducing unnecessary overhead.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Notifications are fully transactional, in that messages are not sent until the transaction they were sent from is committed.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] This eliminates the problem of messages being sent for an action being performed which is then rolled back.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Many connectors for PostgreSQL provide support for this notification system (including libpq, JDBC, Npgsql, psycopg and node.js) so it can be used by external applications.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] PostgreSQL can act as an effective, persistent "pub/sub" server or job server by combining LISTEN with FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Rules allow the "query tree" of an incoming query to be rewritten; they are an, automatically invoked, macro language for SQL.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] "Query Re-Write Rules" are attached to a table/class and "Re-Write" the incoming DML (select, insert, update, and/or delete) into one or more queries that either replace the original DML statement or execute in addition to it.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Query Re-Write occurs after DML statement parsing and before query planning.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] The functionality rules provide was, in almost every way, later duplicated with the introduction of newer types of triggers.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] The use of triggers is usually preferred over rules as it is easier to reason about trigger behavior and interactions than when equivalent rules are used.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] PostgreSQL server is process-based (not threaded), and uses one operating system process per database session.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Multiple sessions are automatically spread across all available CPUs by the operating system.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Many types of queries can also be parallelized across multiple background worker processes, taking advantage of multiple CPUs or cores.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Client applications can use threads and create multiple database connections from each thread.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] PostgreSQL manages its internal security on a per-role basis.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] A role is generally regarded to be a user (a role that can log in), or a group (a role of which other roles are members).
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Permissions can be granted or revoked on any object down to the column level, and can allow or prevent the visibility/creation/alteration/deletion of objects at the database, schema, table, and row levels.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] PostgreSQL's SECURITY LABEL feature (extension to SQL standards), allows for additional security; with a bundled loadable module that supports label-based mandatory access control (MAC) based on Security-Enhanced Linux (SELinux) security policy.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] The GSSAPI, SSPI, Kerberos, peer, ident and certificate methods can also use a specified "map" file that lists which users matched by that authentication system are allowed to connect as a specific database user.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] These methods are specified in the cluster's host-based authentication configuration file (pg_hba.conf), which determines what connections are allowed.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] This allows control over which user can connect to which database, where they can connect from (IP address, IP address range, domain socket), which authentication system will be enforced, and whether the connection must use Transport Layer Security (TLS).
[src:edgedb/postgresql] PostgreSQL claims high, but not complete, conformance with the latest SQL standard ("as of the version 17 release in September 2024, PostgreSQL conforms to at least 170 of the 177 mandatory features for SQL:2023 Core conformance", and no other databases fully conformed to it).
[src:edgedb/postgresql] One exception is the handling of unquoted identifiers like table or column names.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] In PostgreSQL they are folded, internally, to lower case characters whereas the standard says that unquoted identifiers should be folded to upper case.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Thus, `Foo` should be equivalent to `FOO` not `foo` according to the standard.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Other shortcomings concern the absence of temporal tables allowing automatic logging of row versions during transactions with the possibility of browsing in time (FOR SYSTEM TIME predicate), although relatively SQL compliant third-party extensions are available.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Many informal performance studies of PostgreSQL have been done.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Performance improvements aimed at improving scalability began heavily with version 8.1.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Simple benchmarks between version 8.0 and version 8.4 showed that the latter was more than ten times faster on read-only workloads and at least 7.5 times faster on both read and write workloads.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] The first industry-standard and peer-validated benchmark was completed in June 2007, using the Sun Java System Application Server (proprietary version of GlassFish) 9.0 Platform Edition, UltraSPARC T1-based Sun Fire server and PostgreSQL 8.2.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] This result of 778.14 SPECjAppServer2004 JOPS@Standard compares favourably with the 874 JOPS@Standard with Oracle 10 on an Itanium-based HP-UX system.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] In August 2007, Sun submitted an improved benchmark score of 813.73 SPECjAppServer2004 JOPS@Standard.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] With the system under test at a reduced price, the price/performance improved from $84.98/JOPS to $70.57/JOPS.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] The default configuration of PostgreSQL uses only a small amount of dedicated memory for performance-critical purposes such as caching database blocks and sorting.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] This limitation is primarily because older operating systems required kernel changes to allow allocating large blocks of shared memory.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] PostgreSQL.org provides advice on basic recommended performance practice in a wiki.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] In April 2012, Robert Haas of EnterpriseDB demonstrated PostgreSQL 9.2's linear CPU scalability using a server with 64 cores.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Matloob Khushi performed benchmarking between PostgreSQL 9.0 and MySQL 5.6.15 for their ability to process genomic data.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] In his performance analysis he found that PostgreSQL extracts overlapping genomic regions eight times faster than MySQL using two datasets of 80,000 each forming random human DNA regions.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Insertion and data uploads in PostgreSQL were also better, although general searching ability of both databases was almost equivalent.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] 64-bit Power ISA), SPARC (also 64-bit), MIPS and PA-RISC.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] It was also known to work on some other platforms (while not been tested on for years, i.e. for latest versions).
[src:edgedb/postgresql] , which can be used to enter SQL queries directly, or execute them from a file.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] In addition, psql provides a number of meta-commands and various shell-like features to facilitate writing scripts and automating a wide variety of tasks; for example tab completion of object names and SQL syntax.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] (GUI) administration tool for PostgreSQL, which is supported on many computer platforms.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] The program is available in more than a dozen languages.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] The second incarnation (named pgAdmin II) was a complete rewrite, first released on January 16, 2002.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] and then released under the same license as PostgreSQL.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] framework allowing it to run on most common operating systems.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] The query tool includes a scripting language called pgScript for supporting admin and development tasks.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] announced that with the shift towards web-based models, work has begun on pgAdmin 4 with the aim to facilitate cloud deployments.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] PostgreSQL Studio allows users to perform essential PostgreSQL database development tasks from a web-based console.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] PostgreSQL Studio allows users to work with cloud databases without the need to open firewalls.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] AJAX/JavaScript-driven web interface for PostgreSQL.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Allows browsing, maintaining and creating data and database objects via a web browser.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] management for commonly used scripts, among other features.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Installers are available for Windows, Macintosh, and Linux, and a simple cross-platform archive that runs from a script.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Base can be used as a front-end for PostgreSQL.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] The pgBadger PostgreSQL log analyzer generates detailed reports from a PostgreSQL log file.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] pgDevOps is a suite of web tools to install & manage multiple PostgreSQL versions, extensions, and community components, develop SQL queries, monitor running databases and find performance problems.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] is a simple web-based administration tool for PostgreSQL and others, written in PHP.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] pgBackRest is a backup and restore tool for PostgreSQL that provides support for full, differential, and incremental backups.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] pgaudit is a PostgreSQL extension that provides detailed session and/or object audit logging via the standard logging facility provided by PostgreSQL.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Postgresus is an open source backup tool with GUI for scheduled backups with support of external sources (S3, NAS, FTP, Google Drive, Google Cloud, etc.) and notifications to external services (Slack, Discord, Telegram, SMTP, etc.).
[src:edgedb/postgresql] A number of companies offer proprietary tools for PostgreSQL.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] They often consist of a universal core that is adapted for various specific database products.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] These tools mostly share the administration features with the open source tools but offer improvements in data modeling, importing, exporting or reporting.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] Due to its permissive open-source license and extensible architecture, a broad ecosystem has developed around PostgreSQL.
[src:edgedb/postgresql] This includes numerous companies offering dedicated support and hosting, as well as several forks and derivative databases that adapt PostgreSQL for specific workloads.
[src:edgedb/reference-edgeql] EdgeQL is a next-generation query language designed to match SQL in power and surpass it in terms of clarity, brevity, and intuitiveness.
[src:edgedb/reference-edgeql] It's used to query the database, insert/update/delete data, modify/introspect the schema, manage transactions, and more.
[src:edgedb/reference-edgeql] EdgeQL is a spiritual successor to SQL designed with a few core principles in mind.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] A **relational database** (**RDB**) is a database based on the relational model of data, as proposed by E.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] A Relational Database Management System (RDBMS) is a type of database management system that stores data in a structured format using rows and columns.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Many relational database systems are equipped with the option of using SQL (Structured Query Language) for querying and updating the database.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] The concept of relational database was defined by E.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Codd introduced the term *relational* in his research paper "A Relational Model of Data for Large Shared Data Banks".
[src:edgedb/relational-database] In this paper and later papers, he defined what he meant by *relation*.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] One well-known definition of what constitutes a relational database system is composed of Codd's 12 rules.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Provide relational operators to manipulate the data in tabular form.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] In 1974, IBM began developing System R, a research project to develop a prototype RDBMS.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] The first system sold as an RDBMS was Multics Relational Data Store (June 1976).
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Oracle was released in 1979 by Relational Software, now Oracle Corporation.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Other examples of an RDBMS include IBM Db2, SAP Sybase ASE, and Informix.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] In 1984, the first RDBMS for Macintosh began being developed, code-named Silver Surfer, and was released in 1987 as 4th Dimension and known today as 4D.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] The most common definition of an RDBMS is a product that presents a view of data as a collection of rows and columns, even if it is not based strictly upon relational theory.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] By this definition, RDBMS products typically implement some but not all of Codd's 12 rules.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] A second school of thought argues that if a database does not implement all of Codd's rules (or the current understanding on the relational model, as expressed by Christopher J.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Date, Hugh Darwen and others), it is not relational.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] This view, shared by many theorists and other strict adherents to Codd's principles, would disqualify most DBMSs as not relational.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] For clarification, they often refer to some RDBMSs as *truly-relational database management systems* (TRDBMS), naming others *pseudo-relational database management systems* (PRDBMS).
[src:edgedb/relational-database] As of 2009, most commercial relational DBMSs employ SQL as their query language.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Alternative query languages have been proposed and implemented, notably the pre-1996 implementation of Ingres QUEL.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] A relational model organizes data into one or more tables (or "relations") of columns and rows, with a unique key identifying each row.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Generally, each table/relation represents one "entity type" (such as customer or product).
[src:edgedb/relational-database] The rows represent instances of that type of entity (such as "Lee" or "chair") and the columns represent values attributed to that instance (such as address or price).
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Each row in a table has its own unique key.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Rows in a table can be linked to rows in other tables by adding a column for the unique key of the linked row (such columns are known as foreign keys).
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Codd showed that data relationships of arbitrary complexity can be represented by a simple set of concepts.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Part of this processing involves consistently being able to select or modify one and only one row in a table.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Therefore, most physical implementations have a unique primary key (PK) for each row in a table.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] When a new row is written to the table, a new unique value for the primary key is generated; this is the key that the system uses primarily for accessing the table.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] System performance is optimized for PKs.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Other, more natural keys may also be identified and defined as alternate keys (AK).
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Often several columns are needed to form an AK (this is one reason why a single integer column is usually made the PK).
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Both PKs and AKs have the ability to uniquely identify a row within a table.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Additional technology may be applied to ensure a unique ID across the world, a globally unique identifier, when there are broader system requirements.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] The primary keys within a database are used to define the relationships among the tables.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] When a PK migrates to another table, it becomes a foreign key (FK) in the other table.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] When each cell can contain only one value and the PK migrates into a regular entity table, this design pattern can represent either a one-to-one or one-to-many relationship.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Most relational database designs resolve many-to-many relationships by creating an additional table that contains the PKs from both of the other entity tables – the relationship becomes an entity; the resolution table is then named appropriately and the two FKs are combined to form a PK.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] The migration of PKs to other tables is the second major reason why system-assigned integers are used normally as PKs; there is usually neither efficiency nor clarity in migrating a bunch of other types of columns.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Relationships are a logical connection between different tables (entities), established on the basis of interaction among these tables.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] These relationships can be modelled as an entity-relationship model.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] In order for a database management system (DBMS) to operate efficiently and accurately, it must use ACID transactions.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Part of the programming within an RDBMS is accomplished using stored procedures (SPs).
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Often procedures can be used to greatly reduce the amount of information transferred within and outside of a system.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] For increased security, the system design may grant access to only the stored procedures and not directly to the tables.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Fundamental stored procedures contain the logic needed to insert new and update existing data.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] More complex procedures may be written to implement additional rules and logic related to processing or selecting the data.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] The relational database was first defined in June 1970 by Edgar Codd, of IBM's San Jose Research Laboratory.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Codd's view of what qualifies as an RDBMS is summarized in Codd's 12 rules.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] A relational database has become the predominant type of database.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Other models besides the *relational model* include the hierarchical database model and the network model.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] In a relational database, a *relation* is a set of tuples that have the same attributes.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] A tuple usually represents an object and information about that object.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Objects are typically physical objects or concepts.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] A relation is usually described as a table, which is organized into rows and columns.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] All the data referenced by an attribute are in the same domain and conform to the same constraints.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] The relational model specifies that the tuples of a relation have no specific order and that the tuples, in turn, impose no order on the attributes.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Applications access data by specifying queries, which use operations such as *select* to identify tuples, *project* to identify attributes, and *join* to combine relations.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Relations can be modified using the *insert*, *delete*, and *update* operators.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] New tuples can supply explicit values or be derived from a query.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Similarly, queries identify tuples for updating or deleting.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] If the tuple contains a candidate or primary key then obviously it is unique; however, a primary key need not be defined for a row or record to be a tuple.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] The definition of a tuple requires that it be unique, but does not require a primary key to be defined.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Because a tuple is unique, its attributes by definition constitute a superkey.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] All data are stored and accessed via relations.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Relations that store data are called "base relations", and in implementations are called "tables".
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Other relations do not store data, but are computed by applying relational operations to other relations.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] These relations are sometimes called "derived relations".
[src:edgedb/relational-database] In implementations these are called "views" or "queries".
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Derived relations are convenient in that they act as a single relation, even though they may grab information from several relations.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Also, derived relations can be used as an abstraction layer.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] A domain describes the set of possible values for a given attribute, and can be considered a constraint on the value of the attribute.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Mathematically, attaching a domain to an attribute means that any value for the attribute must be an element of the specified set.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] The character string *"ABC"*, for instance, is not in the integer domain, but the integer value *123* is.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Another example of domain describes the possible values for the field "CoinFace" as ("Heads","Tails").
[src:edgedb/relational-database] So, the field "CoinFace" will not accept input values like (0,1) or (H,T).
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Constraints are often used to make it possible to further restrict the domain of an attribute.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] For instance, a constraint can restrict a given integer attribute to values between 1 and 10.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Constraints provide one method of implementing business rules in the database and support subsequent data use within the application layer.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] SQL implements constraint functionality in the form of check constraints.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Constraints restrict the data that can be stored in relations.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] These are usually defined using expressions that result in a Boolean value, indicating whether or not the data satisfies the constraint.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Constraints can apply to single attributes, to a tuple (restricting combinations of attributes) or to an entire relation.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Since every attribute has an associated domain, there are constraints (**domain constraints**).
[src:edgedb/relational-database] The two principal rules for the relational model are known as **entity integrity** and **referential integrity**.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Every relation/table has a primary key, this being a consequence of a relation being a set.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] A primary key uniquely specifies a tuple within a table.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] While natural attributes (attributes used to describe the data being entered) are sometimes good primary keys, surrogate keys are often used instead.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] A surrogate key is an artificial attribute assigned to an object which uniquely identifies it (for instance, in a table of information about students at a school they might all be assigned a student ID in order to differentiate them).
[src:edgedb/relational-database] The surrogate key has no intrinsic (inherent) meaning, but rather is useful through its ability to uniquely identify a tuple.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Another common occurrence, especially in regard to N:M cardinality is the composite key.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] A composite key is a key made up of two or more attributes within a table that (together) uniquely identify a record.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Foreign key refers to a field in a relational table that matches the primary key column of another table.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Foreign keys need not have unique values in the referencing relation.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] A foreign key can be used to cross-reference tables, and it effectively uses the values of attributes in the referenced relation to restrict the domain of one or more attributes in the referencing relation.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] A stored procedure is executable code that is associated with, and generally stored in, the database.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Stored procedures usually collect and customize common operations, like inserting a tuple into a relation, gathering statistical information about usage patterns, or encapsulating complex business logic and calculations.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Frequently they are used as an application programming interface (API) for security or simplicity.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Implementations of stored procedures on SQL RDBMS's often allow developers to take advantage of procedural extensions (often vendor-specific) to the standard declarative SQL syntax.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Stored procedures are not part of the relational database model, but all commercial implementations include them.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] An index is one way of providing quicker access to data.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Indices can be created on any combination of attributes on a relation.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Queries that filter using those attributes can find matching tuples directly using the index (similar to Hash table lookup), without having to check each tuple in turn.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] This is analogous to using the index of a book to go directly to the page on which the information you are looking for is found, so that you do not have to read the entire book to find what you are looking for.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Relational databases typically supply multiple indexing techniques, each of which is optimal for some combination of data distribution, relation size, and typical access pattern.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Indices are usually implemented via B+ trees, R-trees, and bitmaps.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Indices are usually not considered part of the database, as they are considered an implementation detail, though indices are usually maintained by the same group that maintains the other parts of the database.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] The use of efficient indexes on both primary and foreign keys can dramatically improve query performance.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] This is because B-tree indexes result in query times proportional to log(n) where n is the number of rows in a table and hash indexes result in constant time queries (no size dependency as long as the relevant part of the index fits into memory).
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Queries made against the relational database, and the derived relvars in the database are expressed in a relational calculus or a relational algebra.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] In his original relational algebra, Codd introduced eight relational operators in two groups of four operators each.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Other operators have been introduced or proposed since Codd's introduction of the original eight including relational comparison operators and extensions that offer support for nesting and hierarchical data, among others.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Normalization was first proposed by Codd as an integral part of the relational model.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] It encompasses a set of procedures designed to eliminate non-simple domains (non-atomic values) and the redundancy (duplication) of data, which in turn prevents data manipulation anomalies and loss of data integrity.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] The most common forms of normalization applied to databases are called the normal forms.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Connolly and Begg define database management system (DBMS) as a "software system that enables users to define, create, maintain and control access to the database".
[src:edgedb/relational-database] RDBMS is an extension of that initialism that is sometimes used when the underlying database is relational.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] An alternative definition for a **relational database management system** is a database management system (DBMS) based on the relational model.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Most databases in widespread use today are based on this model.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] RDBMSs have been a common option for the storage of information in databases used for financial records, manufacturing and logistical information, personnel data, and other applications since the 1980s.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Relational databases have often replaced legacy hierarchical databases and network databases, because RDBMS were easier to implement and administer.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] However, due to the expanse of technologies, such as horizontal scaling of computer clusters, NoSQL databases have recently become popular as an alternative to RDBMS databases.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] Distributed Relational Database Architecture (DRDA) was designed by a workgroup within IBM in the period 1988 to 1994.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] DRDA enables network connected relational databases to cooperate to fulfill SQL requests.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] The messages, protocols, and structural components of DRDA are defined by the Distributed Data Management Architecture.
[src:edgedb/relational-database] According to research company Gartner, in 2011, the five leading proprietary software relational database vendors by revenue were Oracle (48.8%), IBM (20.2%), Microsoft (17.0%), SAP including Sybase (4.6%), and Teradata (3.7%).
